Notes: "Relative to availability, wolves selected more males (64%) and fewer females (18%) than expected.". According to femur analysis. wolves generally killed "older infirmed elk"
Wolf_Pack_Notes: Recolonized SA in winter 2002
Prey_Notes: "Putatively naive" at beginning of study period. Male elk expend considerable energy during the rut and probably enter winter in poorer physical condition than female elk,  "Logistic regression results of prey selection (full model) indicated that male elk in poor physical condition were most likely to be killed by wolves". The probability of elk occurrence was lower on south aspects, and was greatest in grasslands and shallow slopes (diminished risk of cougar predation but heightened risk of wold predation). Structural complexity of elk kill sites (wolf) increased over the years. "Elk typically move around winter range in groups of 100–200 females"

Wolf_Pack_Notes: Recolonized SA in winter 2002
Prey_Notes: "Putatively naive" at beginning of study period. The probability of mule deer occurrence was higher on south aspects, shrub steppe habitats, and with increasing slopes (most likely to occur in juniper canyon habitats (characterized by steeper slopes and greater hiding cover ~ little risk of wolf predation), and was lower in riparian and grassland habitats. Grouo size ranges from 1-15 individuals

Using figure extract tool and the text the % of 19 elk kills made up by each age class was: 0.5-1 = 26%, 1.5-2=0%, 2.5-5.5=16%, 6.5-10.5=11%, and 11.5-16.5=46%. Based on the following, RB recalculated the data for the whole time period: "Carcass use during the period of intensive tracking (mid-Feb-mid-Mar) was 56% for elk and 40% for moose (Table 2). Assuming that 75% by weight of a carcass was consumable (Peterson 1977), during this 19-day period 854 kg of elk and 407 kg of moose were available to the BL pack. Actual calculated consumption was 478 kg of elk and 163 kg of moose or 25 and 9/kg/day, respectively. Given an average weight of 32.7 kg/wolf, the study pack of 5 animals consumed 0.21 kg of prey/kg of wolf or 34 kg/pack daily."
